The '''limbic lobe''' is an arc-shaped region of [[cerebral cortex|cortex]] on the medial surface of each [[cerebral hemisphere]] of the mammalian brain, consisting of parts of the frontal, parietal and temporal lobes. The term is ambiguous, with some authors including the [[paraterminal gyrus]], the [[subcallosal area]], the [[cingulate gyrus]], the [[parahippocampal gyrus]], the [[dentate gyrus]], the [[hippocampus]] and the [[subiculum]];<ref name=Fix2008>{{cite book |last1= Fix|first1= JD|title= Neuroanatomy|edition= fourth|year= 2008|publisher= Lippincott Williams & Wilkins|location= Philadelphia|isbn= 0-7817-7245-1|page= 6|chapter= Gross anatomy of the brain|chapterurl= http://books.google.com.au/books?id=6WM1jnDJNe4C&pg=PA6&dq=%22f.+limbic+lobe%22&cd=1#v=onepage&q=%22f.%20limbic%20lobe%22&f=false}}</ref> while the [[Terminologia Anatomica]] includes the [[cingulate sulcus]], the cingulate gyrus, the [[isthmus of cingulate gyrus]], the [http://www.med.wayne.edu/diagRadiology/Limbic%20System%20RSNA%202004/Overview.html fasciolar gyrus], the parahippocampal gyrus, the parahippocampal sulcus, the [[dentate gyrus]], the fimbrodentate sulcus, the [[fimbria of hippocampus]], the [[collateral fissure|collateral sulcus]], and the [[rhinal sulcus]], and omits the hippocampus.

[[Paul Broca|Broca]] named the limbic lobe in 1878, identifying it with the cingulate and parahippocampal gyri, and associating it with the sense of smell - [[Gottfried Reinhold Treviranus|Treviranus]] having earlier noted that, between species, the size of the parahippocampal gyrus varies with the size of the olfactory nerve.<ref name= Finger2001>{{cite book |last1= Finger|first1= S|title= Origins of neuroscience: a history of explorations into brain function|edition= |year= 2001|publisher= Oxford University Press|location= Oxford/NewYork|isbn= 0-19-506503-4|page= 286|chapter= Defining and controlling the circuits of emotion|chapterurl= http://books.google.com.au/books?id=_GMeW9E1IB4C&pg=PA286&dq=%22the+great+limbic+lobe+of+broca%22&cd=1#v=onepage&q=%22the%20great%20limbic%20lobe%20of%20broca%22&f=true}}</ref> In 1937 [[James Papez|Papez]] theorized that a circuit including the [[hippocampal formation]] and the cingulate gyrus constitutes the neural substrate of emotional behavior,<ref name= Papez1937>{{cite journal |last1= Papez|first1= JW|title= A proposed mechanism of emotion|journal= Archives of neurology and psychiatry|year= 1937|volume= 38|pages= 725–43}}</ref> and [[Heinrich Klüver|Klüver]] and [[Paul Bucy|Bucy]] reported that, in monkeys, [[Segmental resection|resection]] involving the hippocampal formation and the [[amygdala|amygdaloid complex]] has a profound effect on emotional responses.<ref name= Klüver1937>{{cite journal |last1= Klüver|first1= H|last2= Bucy|first2= PC|title= "Psychic blindness" and other symptoms following bilateral temporal lobectomy in Rhesus monkeys|journal= American Journal of Physiology|year= 1937|volume= 119|pages= 352–53|pmid= |doi= |url= }}</ref><ref name= Klüver1939>{{cite journal |last1= Klüver |first1= H|last2= Bucy|first2= PC|title= Preliminary analysis of functions of the temporal lobes in monkeys|journal= Archives of Neurology and psychiatry|year= 1939|volume= 42|pages= 979–1000}}</ref> As a consequence of these publications, the idea that the entire limbic lobe is dedicated to [[olfaction]] receded, and a direct connection between emotion and the limbic lobe was established.<ref name= Nieuwenhuys2008>{{cite book |last1= Nieuwenhuys|first1= R|last2= Voogd|first2= J|last3= van Huijzen|first3= C|title= The human central nervous system|edition= fourth|year= 2008|publisher= Springer-Verlag|location= Berlin/Heidelberg/New York|isbn= 3-540-13441-7|page= 917|chapter= The greater limbic system|chapterurl= http://books.google.com.au/books?id=vAiFe7gZLhoC&pg=PT916&dq=%22from+limbic+lobe+to+limbic+system%22&cd=1#v=onepage&q=%22from%20limbic%20lobe%20to%20limbic%20system%22&f=true}}</ref>

